1000th lucky number is 777747447.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= k <= 10⁹`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/find-the-k-th-lucky-number/","problemName":"Find The K-th Lucky Number","problemNumber":2802,"problemSlug":"find-the-k-th-lucky-number","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2802,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write a generator function that takes an integer `n` as an argument and returns a generator object which yields the **factorial sequence**.\n\nThe **factorial sequence** is defined by the relation `n! = n * (n-1) * (n-2) * ... * 2 * 1.`\n\nThe factorial of 0 is defined as 1.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 5\nOutput: [1,2,6,24,120]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(5)\ngen.next().value // 1\ngen.next().value // 2\ngen.next().value // 6\ngen.next().value // 24\ngen.next().value // 120","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: n = 2\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(2) \ngen.next().value // 1 \ngen.next().value // 2 ","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: n = 0\nOutput: [1]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(0) \ngen.next().value // 1 ","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= n <= 18`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Write a generator function that takes an integer `n` as an argument and returns a generator object which yields the **factorial sequence**.\n\nThe **factorial sequence** is defined by the relation `n! = n * (n-1) * (n-2) * ... * 2 * 1.`\n\nThe factorial of 0 is defined as 1.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: n = 5\nOutput: [1,2,6,24,120]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(5)\ngen.next().value // 1\ngen.next().value // 2\ngen.next().value // 6\ngen.next().value // 24\ngen.next().value // 120\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: n = 2\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(2) \ngen.next().value // 1 \ngen.next().value // 2\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: n = 0\nOutput: [1]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(0) \ngen.next().value // 1\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= n <= 18`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/factorial-generator/","problemName":"Factorial Generator","problemNumber":2803,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write a generator function that takes an integer `n` as an argument and returns a generator object which yields the **factorial sequence**.\n\nThe **factorial sequence** is defined by the relation `n! = n * (n-1) * (n-2) * ... * 2 * 1.`\n\nThe factorial of 0 is defined as 1.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: n = 5\nOutput: [1,2,6,24,120]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(5)\ngen.next().value // 1\ngen.next().value // 2\ngen.next().value // 6\ngen.next().value // 24\ngen.next().value // 120","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: n = 2\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(2) \ngen.next().value // 1 \ngen.next().value // 2 ","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: n = 0\nOutput: [1]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(0) \ngen.next().value // 1 ","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= n <= 18`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Write a generator function that takes an integer `n` as an argument and returns a generator object which yields the **factorial sequence**.\n\nThe **factorial sequence** is defined by the relation `n! = n * (n-1) * (n-2) * ... * 2 * 1.`\n\nThe factorial of 0 is defined as 1.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: n = 5\nOutput: [1,2,6,24,120]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(5)\ngen.next().value // 1\ngen.next().value // 2\ngen.next().value // 6\ngen.next().value // 24\ngen.next().value // 120\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: n = 2\nOutput: [1,2]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(2) \ngen.next().value // 1 \ngen.next().value // 2\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: n = 0\nOutput: [1]\nExplanation: \nconst gen = factorial(0) \ngen.next().value // 1\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `0 <= n <= 18`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/factorial-generator/","problemName":"Factorial Generator","problemNumber":2803,"problemSlug":"factorial-generator","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2803,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["JavaScript"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write your version of method `forEach` that enhances all arrays such that you can call the `array.forEach(callback, context)` method on any array and it will execute `callback` on each element of the array. Method `forEach` should not return anything.\n\n`callback` accepts the following arguments:\n\n- `currentValue` - represents the current element being processed in the array. It is the value of the element in the current iteration.\n\n- `index` - represents the index of the current element being processed in the array.\n\n- `array` - represents the array itself, allowing access to the entire array within the callback function.\n\nThe `context` is the object that should be passed as the function context parameter to the `callback` function, ensuring that the `this` keyword within the `callback` function refers to this `context` object.\n\nTry to implement it without using the built-in array methods.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: \narr = [1,2,3], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = val * 2, \ncontext = {\"context\":true}\nOutput: [2,4,6]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context)  \nconsole.log(arr) // [2,4,6]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = this, \ncontext = {\"context\": false}\nOutput: [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context) \nconsole.log(arr) // [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array with the right context.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = !val, \ncontext = {\"context\": 5}\nOutput: [false,false,true,true]","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `arr` is a valid JSON array\n\n- `context` is a valid JSON object\n\n- `fn` is a function\n\n- `0 <= arr.length <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["JavaScript"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Easy","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"Write your version of method `forEach` that enhances all arrays such that you can call the `array.forEach(callback, context)` method on any array and it will execute `callback` on each element of the array. Method `forEach` should not return anything.\n\n`callback` accepts the following arguments:\n\n- `currentValue` - represents the current element being processed in the array. It is the value of the element in the current iteration.\n\n- `index` - represents the index of the current element being processed in the array.\n\n- `array` - represents the array itself, allowing access to the entire array within the callback function.\n\nThe `context` is the object that should be passed as the function context parameter to the `callback` function, ensuring that the `this` keyword within the `callback` function refers to this `context` object.\n\nTry to implement it without using the built-in array methods.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: \narr = [1,2,3], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = val * 2, \ncontext = {\"context\":true}\nOutput: [2,4,6]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context)  \nconsole.log(arr) // [2,4,6]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = this, \ncontext = {\"context\": false}\nOutput: [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context) \nconsole.log(arr) // [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array with the right context.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = !val, \ncontext = {\"context\": 5}\nOutput: [false,false,true,true]\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `arr` is a valid JSON array\n\n- `context` is a valid JSON object\n\n- `fn` is a function\n\n- `0 <= arr.length <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/array-prototype-foreach/","problemName":"Array Prototype ForEach","problemNumber":2804,"revisionAnchorAt":0,"revisionCount":0,"revisionDates":[],"revisionPlanHours":[1,24,168,336,672],"solutionCode":"","testCases":"","updatedAt":0},"descriptionBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"Write your version of method `forEach` that enhances all arrays such that you can call the `array.forEach(callback, context)` method on any array and it will execute `callback` on each element of the array. Method `forEach` should not return anything.\n\n`callback` accepts the following arguments:\n\n- `currentValue` - represents the current element being processed in the array. It is the value of the element in the current iteration.\n\n- `index` - represents the index of the current element being processed in the array.\n\n- `array` - represents the array itself, allowing access to the entire array within the callback function.\n\nThe `context` is the object that should be passed as the function context parameter to the `callback` function, ensuring that the `this` keyword within the `callback` function refers to this `context` object.\n\nTry to implement it without using the built-in array methods.\n\n**Example 1:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":1,"text":"Input: \narr = [1,2,3], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = val * 2, \ncontext = {\"context\":true}\nOutput: [2,4,6]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context)  \nconsole.log(arr) // [2,4,6]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array.","type":"code"},{"sequence":2,"text":"**Example 2:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":3,"text":"Input: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = this, \ncontext = {\"context\": false}\nOutput: [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context) \nconsole.log(arr) // [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array with the right context.","type":"code"},{"sequence":4,"text":"**Example 3:**","type":"text"},{"sequence":5,"text":"Input: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = !val, \ncontext = {\"context\": 5}\nOutput: [false,false,true,true]","type":"code"},{"sequence":6,"text":"**Constraints:**\n\n- `arr` is a valid JSON array\n\n- `context` is a valid JSON object\n\n- `fn` is a function\n\n- `0 <= arr.length <= 10⁵`","type":"text"}],"difficulty":"Easy","examples":[],"paidOnly":false,"problem":"Write your version of method `forEach` that enhances all arrays such that you can call the `array.forEach(callback, context)` method on any array and it will execute `callback` on each element of the array. Method `forEach` should not return anything.\n\n`callback` accepts the following arguments:\n\n- `currentValue` - represents the current element being processed in the array. It is the value of the element in the current iteration.\n\n- `index` - represents the index of the current element being processed in the array.\n\n- `array` - represents the array itself, allowing access to the entire array within the callback function.\n\nThe `context` is the object that should be passed as the function context parameter to the `callback` function, ensuring that the `this` keyword within the `callback` function refers to this `context` object.\n\nTry to implement it without using the built-in array methods.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\nInput: \narr = [1,2,3], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = val * 2, \ncontext = {\"context\":true}\nOutput: [2,4,6]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context)  \nconsole.log(arr) // [2,4,6]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\nInput: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = this, \ncontext = {\"context\": false}\nOutput: [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\nExplanation: \narr.forEach(callback, context) \nconsole.log(arr) // [{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false},{\"context\":false}]\n\nThe callback is executed on each element of the array with the right context.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\nInput: \narr = [true, true, false, false], \ncallback = (val, i, arr) => arr[i] = !val, \ncontext = {\"context\": 5}\nOutput: [false,false,true,true]\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `arr` is a valid JSON array\n\n- `context` is a valid JSON object\n\n- `fn` is a function\n\n- `0 <= arr.length <= 10⁵`","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/array-prototype-foreach/","problemName":"Array Prototype ForEach","problemNumber":2804,"problemSlug":"array-prototype-foreach","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2804,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categorie