. The maximum number that can be made with the remaining digits is \"100\". So the answer is \"1001\".\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= s.length <= 100`\n\n- `s` consists only of `'0'` and `'1'`.\n\n- `s` contains at least one `'1'`.","problemLink":"https://leetcode.com/problems/maximum-odd-binary-number/","problemName":"Maximum Odd Binary Number","problemNumber":2864,"problemSlug":"maximum-odd-binary-number","schemaVersion":2,"sequenceIndex":2864,"solutionApproaches":[]},{"assets":[],"categories":["Array","Stack","Monotonic Stack"],"constraintBlocks":[],"contentBlocks":[{"sequence":0,"text":"You are given an array `heights` of `n` integers representing the number of bricks in `n` consecutive towers. Your task is to remove some bricks to form a **mountain-shaped** tower arrangement. In this arrangement, the tower heights are non-decreasing, reaching a maximum peak value with one or multiple consecutive towers and then non-increasing.\n\nReturn the **maximum possible sum** of heights of a mountain-shaped tower arrangement.\n\n**Example 1:**\n\n**Input:** heights = [5,3,4,1,1]\n\n**Output:** 13\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nWe remove some bricks to make `heights = [5,3,3,1,1]`, the peak is at index 0.\n\n**Example 2:**\n\n**Input:** heights = [6,5,3,9,2,7]\n\n**Output:** 22\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nWe remove some bricks to make `heights = [3,3,3,9,2,2]`, the peak is at index 3.\n\n**Example 3:**\n\n**Input:** heights = [3,2,5,5,2,3]\n\n**Output:** 18\n\n**Explanation:**\n\nWe remove some bricks to make `heights = [2,2,5,5,2,2]`, the peak is at index 2 or 3.\n\n**Constraints:**\n\n- `1 <= n == heights.length <= 10³`\n\n- `1 <= heights[i] <= 10⁹`","type":"text"}],"contentHtml":"","contentHtmlLocal":"","databaseEntry":{"categories":["Array","Stack","Monotonic Stack"],"createdAt":0,"difficulty":"Medium","lastRevisionAt":0,"problem":"You are given an array `heights` of `n` integers representing the number of bricks in `n` consecutive towers. Your task is to remove some bricks to form